Redesign the Sprint Output Submission Form page with the following UI/UX fixes. Maintain HSBC branding (red/white color scheme) and all existing functionality.
1. Team Selection — Make it the first step, not a hidden corner dropdown

Move the team selector from the top-right corner to a full-width, prominent position directly below the page title
Make it a clearly labeled step (e.g., "Step 1: Select Your Team / End-to-End Process") so users cannot miss it
Consider using card-style selectors or a large full-width dropdown instead of a small corner dropdown
Only reveal the rest of the form after a team is selected

2. Unsaved Changes Alert — Convert from inline banner to a proper modal

Replace the current inline red banner with a centered modal overlay with a dimmed backdrop
The modal should clearly explain the consequence of switching teams (discarding unsaved work)
Use clear action buttons: "Discard & Switch" (destructive, red) and "Cancel" (neutral)

3. Error Handling — Fix the "Failed to load team data" message

Add a "Retry" button next to the error message
Include a brief user-friendly explanation (e.g., "We couldn't load your team data. Check your connection and try again.")
Style it as a dismissible alert component, not just floating red text

4. Remove conflicting state indicators

Do not show two different team names simultaneously (dropdown vs "Currently editing" badge)
Show only one clear indicator of which team the user is currently working in

5. Improve tab navigation (Sprints / Meetings / Reading & Viewing)

Add a clear bottom border or underline for the active tab
Add more visual separation between the tabs and the content area below
Ensure inactive tabs have hover states

6. Improve form field clarity

Visually tie each question label directly to its input field with tighter spacing
Add placeholder text inside inputs to guide responses
Group related fields with subtle card backgrounds or section dividers

7. Fix the background

Replace the mountain background image with a solid white or light gray background behind the form content area
If the image must stay, add a solid white card/container with proper padding so text never overlaps the image

8. Add a progress indicator

Add a progress bar or step indicator showing which sprints have been completed and which are remaining
Position it near the top of the form area so users always know where they stand

Keep all existing form fields, sprint content, and submission logic intact. Focus on layout, hierarchy, readability, and error handling improvements.
